

The numbers are placed in “layers’’ around the centre.

* The centre is 1.  
* The first layer (distance 1) contains the six numbers 2,…,7.  
* In general the layer at distance \(L\;(L\ge 1)\) has \(6L\) cells.  

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1.  Which layer contains 2026?

The total number of cells up to layer \(L\) is  

\[
f(L)=1+3L(L+1).
\]

We need the smallest \(L\) with \(f(L)\ge 2026\).

\[
3L^{2}+3L+1\ge 2026\Longrightarrow L^{2}+L-675\ge0
\]
gives \(L=26\) (since \(f(25)=1951<2026\) and \(f(26)=2107\ge2026\)).  
Hence 2026 lies in the 26‑th layer.

The first number of layer \(L\) is  

\[
s(L)=f(L-1)+1=2+3(L-1)L .
\]

For \(L=26\),

\[
s(26)=2+3\cdot25\cdot26=1952 .
\]

Thus the position of 2026 inside its layer is  

\[
k=2026-s(26)=74 .
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2.  Coordinates of the cells  

Use axial coordinates \((q,r)\) with the six neighbour vectors  

\[
\begin{aligned}
E&=(1,0),&\;NE&=(1,-1),&\;NW&=(0,-1),\\
W&=(-1,0),&\;SW&=(-1,1),&\;SE&=(0,1).
\end{aligned}
\]

The first cell of a layer (its “east’’ corner) is \((L,0)\).  
Going round the layer we move

\[
NW\;(L\text{ steps}),\;W\;(L),\;SW\;(L),\;SE\;(L),\;E\;(L),\;NE\;(L-1).
\]

For our layer \(L=26\) the indices are

\[
\begin{aligned}
&0\;(=\text{start}),\;1\text{–}26&\;(NW),\\
&27\text{–}52&\;(W),\\
&53\text{–}78&\;(SW),\\
&79\text{–}104&\;(SE),\\
&105\text{–}130&\;(E),\\
&131\text{–}155&\;(NE).
\end{aligned}
\]

Because \(k=74\) lies in the \(SW\) segment, put  

\[
u=k-2L=74-52=22 .
\]

The coordinates are therefore  

\[
(q,r)=(-u,\,-L+u)=(-22,\,-4).
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3.  Neighbours of \((-22,-4)\)

Add the six direction vectors:

\[
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
\text{direction} & (\Delta q,\Delta r) & \text{neighbour coordinate}\\ \hline
E        & ( 1, 0) & (-21,-4)\\
NE       & ( 1,-1) & (-21,-5)\\
NW       & ( 0,-1) & (-22,-5)\\
W        & (-1, 0) & (-23,-4)\\
SW       & (-1, 1) & (-23,-3)\\
SE       & ( 0, 1) & (-22,-3)
\end{array}
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 4.  Numbers of the neighbour cells  

For a coordinate \((q,r)\) the distance from the centre is  

\[
L'=\max\{|q|,|r|,|-q-r|\}.
\]

If \(L'>0\) the index of the cell inside its layer is  

\[
i=
\begin{cases}
q+r=-L'           & \text{(SW side, }q<0),\\[2mm]
\text{(as above)} & \text{similar formulas for the other sides}.
\end{cases}
\]

The number attached to the cell is \(s(L')+i\).

Carrying this out for the six neighbours gives  

\[
\begin{aligned}
(-21,-4)&\rightarrow 1873,\\
(-21,-5)&\rightarrow 2025,\\
(-22,-5)&\rightarrow 2184,\\
(-23,-4)&\rightarrow 2185,\\
(-23,-3)&\rightarrow 2027,\\
(-22,-3)&\rightarrow 1874 .
\end{aligned}
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 5.  Sum of the six neighbours

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Sigma &=1873+2025+2184+2185+2027+1874\\
      &= (1873+1874)+(2025+2027)+(2184+2185)\\
      &= 3747+4052+4369\\
      &= 12168 .
\end{aligned}
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
\[
\boxed{12168}
\]
